      {
        "user": "How does \"lexical reachability\" differ from vocabulary coverage?",
        "assistant": "# Lexical Reachability vs. Vocabulary Coverage\n\nThese two terms come from **very different fields**, despite both involving the word \"lexical.\" Let me clarify the distinction.\n\n## Quick Summary\n\n| Aspect | Lexical Reachability | Vocabulary Coverage |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Field** | Program analysis / compilers | Linguistics / language learning / NLP |\n| **\"Lexical\" refers to** | Textual/syntactic structure of code | Words (lexicon) of a language |\n| **Measures** | Whether a code point can reach another | What % of words in a text a learner/model knows |\n| **Object of study** | Programs | Texts or corpora |\n\n## Lexical Reachability (recap)\n\nA **structural property of code**: can point `A` reach point `B` by following the program's written control flow? It's about **paths through source code**.\n\n## Vocabulary Coverage\n\nA **statistical property of text**: what proportion of the word tokens (or types) in a text are covered by a given vocabulary list?\n\n**Formula (typical):**\n```\nCoverage = (tokens in text known by vocabulary) / (total tokens in text)\n```\n\n### Common Uses\n\n1. **Second-language acquisition** – Research suggests learners need ~95–98% vocabulary coverage to read a text comfortably without a dictionary.\n2. **Corpus linguistics** – Measuring how well a word list (e.g., the 2,000 most frequent English words) covers general or specialized texts.\n3. **NLP / tokenization** – Evaluating how well a model's vocabulary (e.g., a BPE tokenizer's subword inventory) covers a target corpus, affecting out-of-vocabulary (OOV) rates.\n4. **Dictionary/textbook design** – Choosing which words to include for maximum utility.\n\n### Example\n\nIf a text has 1,000 words and a learner knows 950 of them:\n- Vocabulary coverage = 95%\n- The remaining 5% are **unknown words** that may impede comprehension.\n\n## Why the Confusion?\n\nBoth terms use **\"lexical\"**, but in different senses:\n\n- In **programming languages**: \"lexical\" means *pertaining to the textual form of the program* (as in \"lexical scope,\" \"lexer/tokenizer\"). It traces back to treating source code as a sequence of lexemes/tokens.\n- In **linguistics**: \"lexical\" means *pertaining to the lexicon* (words of a language).\n\nSo \"lexical reachability\" is about **reaching code locations**, while \"vocabulary coverage\" is about **knowing enough words**.\n\n## Is There a Connection?\n\nOnly loosely:\n- Both involve **static analysis of text** (code vs. natural language).\n- Both can be framed as **set-membership questions**: \"Is this point reachable?\" vs. \"Is this word in my vocabulary?\"\n- In **NLP**, one *could* speak of \"lexical coverage\" of a tokenizer—how well its token inventory handles a corpus—which is closer to vocabulary coverage than to reachability.\n\n## When Might They Both Apply?\n\nIn **NLP system design**, you might care about:\n- **Vocabulary coverage**: Does my tokenizer handle the input text's words?\n- **Reachability** (in a different sense): Can my model's code paths actually process certain inputs?\n\nBut these remain conceptually distinct.\n\n---\n\nWould you like me to explore a related concept, such as **lexical coverage in NLP tokenizers**, or compare lexical reachability to other code-analysis notions like **definite assignment** or **liveness**?",
