        "assistant": "# Lexical Reachability\n\n**Lexical reachability** is a concept from formal language theory and program analysis that extends the classical notion of graph reachability by adding constraints based on a formal language (typically a context-free language).\n\n## The Basic Idea\n\nIn ordinary graph reachability, you ask: *\"Can I get from node A to node B by following edges?\"*\n\nIn lexical reachability (more commonly called **language-constrained reachability** or **CFL-reachability**), the edges of the graph are labeled with symbols, and a path is only considered \"valid\" if the sequence of labels along it forms a string belonging to some specified formal language *L*.\n\nSo the question becomes: *\"Can I get from A to B along a path whose edge labels spell out a word in language L?\"*\n\n## Common Variants\n\n- **Regular reachability**: The constraint language *L* is a regular language. This is solvable in polynomial time using product constructions with finite automata.\n- **CFL-reachability (Context-Free Language reachability)**: *L* is a context-free language. This is the most studied variant and is solvable in O(n³) time, where n is the number of nodes.\n- **Dyck reachability**: A special case where *L* is the Dyck language (matched parentheses). Very common in practice.\n\n## Why It Matters\n\nLexical/CFL-reachability is foundational in **program analysis**, including:\n\n- **Interprocedural dataflow analysis** — matching call/return edges (which form a Dyck language) ensures you only consider realizable execution paths.\n- **Pointer/alias analysis** — determining which memory locations a pointer might reference.\n- **Taint analysis** — tracking whether tainted data can flow to a sensitive sink.\n- **Type-based analyses** — checking field accesses match field stores.\n\nFor example, when analyzing function calls in a program, a \"call\" edge labeled `(_i` must be matched by a corresponding \"return\" edge `)_i`. Plain reachability would falsely report that data can flow from one caller to another via a shared callee, but Dyck-reachability correctly enforces matching.\n\n## Are You Asking About Something Specific?\n\nIf you encountered the term \"lexical reachability\" in a particular context (e.g., a specific paper, compiler textbook, or scope analysis), let me know and I can tailor the answer — sometimes the term is used informally to describe **lexical scoping** reachability (which identifiers are reachable from a given scope based on lexical nesting).",
