        "user": "How does \"lexical reachability\" differ from vocabulary coverage?",
        "assistant": "Before answering, I want to flag again: I'm treating \"lexical reachability\" here as the construct *you* defined in your previous message (the cold-state vs. post-definition distinguishability gap), not as established terminology. With that caveat, here's how the two concepts differ:\n\n## Vocabulary Coverage\n\nVocabulary coverage asks a **static, binary-ish question**: *Is this term in the model's vocabulary / training distribution?* Typical operationalizations:\n\n- Is the term a single token, or how does the tokenizer fragment it?\n- Does the term appear in training data, and at what frequency?\n- Can the model produce or recognize the surface form?\n\nIt's fundamentally about **presence** — whether the symbol is \"known\" to the model at all.\n\n## Lexical Reachability (per your definition)\n\nLexical reachability asks a **dynamic, differential question**: *How much does an in-context definition change the model's ability to discriminate this term from its near-neighbors?* Key differences:\n\n| Dimension | Vocabulary Coverage | Lexical Reachability |\n|---|---|---|\n| **What it measures** | Presence/familiarity of a token | Gap between cold-state and post-definition distinguishability |\n| **Granularity** | Per-term | Per (model × term × near-neighbor) cell |\n| **Baseline** | Training corpus or tokenizer | Model's own cold-state behavior |\n| **Comparison class** | None (or full vocabulary) | Named near-neighbors |\n| **What it reveals** | Whether the model has seen the term | Whether one sentence of context can install a usable distinction |\n\n## The Conceptual Gap\n\nA term can have **high vocabulary coverage but low lexical reachability**: the model \"knows\" the word but can't sharpen its meaning against neighbors even after a definition (suggesting the representation is rigid or the neighbors are too entangled).\n\nConversely, a term can have **zero vocabulary coverage but high lexical reachability**: a totally novel coinage that the model nevertheless picks up cleanly from one sentence of context, distinguishing it crisply from named neighbors.\n\nThat second case is where the construct seems most diagnostically interesting — it would isolate something like *in-context conceptual uptake* from *prior exposure*.\n\n## A Caveat on the Construct Itself\n\nIf you're developing this metric, a few things I'd want to see pinned down:\n- How is \"distinguishability\" scored? (Logit differences on a forced choice? Embedding distances? Behavioral discrimination on probe questions?)\n- How are \"near-neighbors\" selected, and by whom? (Their choice will dominate results.)\n- Is the gap measured as a difference, ratio, or normalized score? Each has different failure modes when cold-state distinguishability is near floor or ceiling.\n\nHappy to dig into any of these if it's useful for what you're working on.",
