        "user": "How does \"lexical reachability\" differ from graph reachability?",
        "assistant": "Same caveat as before: I'm treating \"lexical reachability\" as the construct *you* defined (the cold-state vs. post-definition distinguishability gap on LLMs), not as established terminology. With that in mind:\n\n## Graph Reachability\n\nGraph reachability is a **structural question over a discrete relation**: *Given a graph G = (V, E) and nodes A, B, does there exist a path from A to B?*\n\n- **Object**: a graph (nodes and edges)\n- **Answer type**: Boolean (yes/no), or sometimes a path/distance\n- **Determined by**: the edge set, fixed in advance\n- **Mathematics**: combinatorial / algorithmic (BFS, DFS, transitive closure)\n- **Variants**: language-constrained reachability (CFL-reachability, Dyck-reachability) refine this by requiring path labels to form a string in some formal language\n\nIt's a property of a **structure**, computed by **traversal**.\n\n## Lexical Reachability (per your definition)\n\n- **Object**: a model's behavior on a term, relative to named near-neighbors, before and after an in-context definition\n- **Answer type**: a continuous score per (model × term × near-neighbor) cell\n- **Determined by**: the model's representations and how they update under in-context information\n- **Mathematics**: statistical / behavioral (a delta between two distinguishability measurements)\n\nIt's a property of a **learned system's responsiveness**, measured by **probing**.\n\n## The Core Differences\n\n| Dimension | Graph Reachability | Lexical Reachability |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Domain** | Discrete graph | Neural model + linguistic stimuli |\n| **What \"reach\" means** | Existence of a connecting path | Magnitude of representational shift induced by a definition |\n| **Output** | Boolean or path | Continuous gap score |\n| **Source of structure** | Explicit edges | Implicit in learned weights + context window |\n| **Time dimension** | Static | Inherently before/after (cold vs. post-introduction) |\n| **Unit of analysis** | Node pair | (Model × term × near-neighbor) triple |\n\n## The Deeper Conceptual Mismatch\n\nGraph reachability asks whether a connection **exists**. Lexical reachability (as you've defined it) asks how much a connection's **discriminative power** changes when a single piece of evidence is injected. The first is existential and structural; the second is differential and epistemic.\n\nA loose analogy might say: in graph reachability, the edges are given and you compute closures; in lexical reachability, you're asking how readily a new \"edge\" (the definition) reshapes the model's local geometry around a term. But that analogy is metaphorical at best — there's no literal graph being traversed in your construct, so I wouldn't lean on it.\n\n## One Honest Note\n\nThe shared word \"reachability\" invites comparison, but the constructs come from genuinely different mathematical traditions (combinatorics vs. behavioral measurement of learned systems). The naming choice is suggestive but, on its face, the two metrics aren't variants of a common formal object — they just both use the metaphor of \"can X get to Y.\" Whether that metaphor is doing useful work in your framework or is mostly evocative is something worth pinning down if you're publishing on it.",
